Author 

Ouadi Maakoul

Independent Researcher

Rabat, Morocco

Abstract 

The next generation of human-rated lunar return vehicles must reconcile two conflicting demands: the extreme performance required for high-mass, high-precision landing and the deterministic, verifiable safety required for crew survival. Current entry capsules rely on passive, fixed-geometry aeroshells and model-dependent guidance, rendering them vulnerable to atmospheric uncertainty and hardware degradation. This paper introduces the Adaptive Deployable Intelligent Capsule (ADIC) , a unified entry architecture that integrates a deployable aeroshell with a certifiably safe, hybrid control stack across fourteen interconnected subsystems.

The core innovation lies in the marriage of two distinct control theories: Control Barrier Functions (CBF) for hard constraint enforcement and the Simplex Architecture for fail-operational switching. We present a formal mathematical framework proving that the system remains forward invariant in the safe set $\mathcal{C}$ regardless of the behavior of uncertified adaptive neural controllers. This is achieved via a real-time CBF-Quadratic Program (QP) filter that projects aggressive AI-guided bank angle and drag modulation commands onto a provably safe manifold.

The paper systematically develops the complete capsule architecture: a hybrid inflatable/mechanical deployable aeroshell, a multi-layer Thermal Protection System (TPS), an embedded sensor network for real-time density estimation, adaptive guidance laws, formal safety-critical control verification, trajectory mode logic, human-rated fault tolerance, and a comprehensive limitations and risk analysis. We provide a complete computational specification demonstrating worst-case execution time feasibility on radiation-hardened flight processors and a stochastic Monte Carlo verification protocol confirming a $3\sigma$ landing dispersion of $\le 100$ m. This work provides the first end-to-end certification roadmap for integrating adaptive, AI-driven guidance with the deterministic safety guarantees required for human deep-space return.

