3.2 Subsystem Descriptions

3.2.1 Deployable Aeroshell System (DAS)
The DAS is a variable-geometry aerodynamic decelerator. Stowed within the launch vehicle payload fairing, it deploys post-trans-lunar injection (TLI) or prior to atmospheric interface. The system combines an inflatable toroidal structure (for volume-efficient expansion) with a mechanically deployed rib framework (for structural integrity at peak dynamic pressure). The deployment state $\delta(t) \in [0,1]$ modulates the effective drag area $A_{eff}$, providing direct control authority over the ballistic coefficient $\beta = m / (C_D A_{eff})$. Detailed mechanical design, deployment dynamics, and aerodynamic characterization are provided in Chapter 4.

3.2.2 Hybrid Thermal Protection System (HTPS)
The HTPS is a multi-layer shield designed to withstand peak stagnation heating while providing a stable structural foundation for the embedded sensor network. The layers comprise: (1) an outer ablative layer (Avcoat/PICA-class) for sacrificial cooling during peak heat pulse; (2) a high-temperature insulating char stabilizer; and (3) a 3D-woven hot structure (HEEET-class) that retains load-bearing capacity at elevated temperatures. The system is designed with variable thickness distribution optimized for the asymmetric heating of a lifting entry. Detailed material specifications and thermal response modeling are provided in Chapter 5.

3.2.3 Embedded Sensor Network (ESN)
Transforming the heat shield from a passive barrier into an active sensing surface, the ESN consists of distributed heat flux gauges, surface thermocouples, pressure transducers, and strain gauges integrated within the HTPS layers. This network provides real-time, spatially resolved measurements of the aerodynamic and aerothermal environment. The data stream is fused with the Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) to estimate atmospheric density $\rho(h)$, aerodynamic coefficients $C_L, C_D$, and the instantaneous heat load distribution. Chapter 6 details the sensor suite, data fusion algorithms, and the bounded-error state estimation guarantee.

3.2.4 Adaptive Guidance and Control (AGC)
The AGC stack implements a hierarchical control strategy. A certified baseline Predictor-Corrector (NPC) algorithm provides a safe, sub-optimal reference trajectory. A Neural Atmospheric Density Estimator (NADE) corrects the onboard atmospheric model in real-time. An uncertified Reinforcement Learning (RL) policy, trained offline across millions of dispersed entry scenarios, generates high-performance bank angle commands $u_a$ to minimize terminal landing dispersion. Chapter 7 presents the guidance laws, the NADE architecture, and the RL training methodology.

3.2.5 Safety-Critical Control Core (SCCC)
The SCCC is the architectural keystone that enables human-rating. It comprises a Safety Monitor, a Simplex decision logic block, and a Control Barrier Function Quadratic Program (CBF-QP) filter. The Safety Monitor evaluates the proposed adaptive command $u_a$ for constraint violations. If the command is deemed safe, it is passed to the CBF-QP filter; otherwise, the system falls back to the certified baseline $u_b$. The CBF-QP filter projects any incoming command onto the set $\mathcal{U}_{safe}$ that guarantees forward invariance of the safety constraints (heat flux, load factor, dynamic pressure). Chapter 8 provides the complete mathematical formalization of this subsystem, including the proof of safety and real-time computational guarantees.

3.3 Operational Sequence

1. Pre-Entry (Exo-atmospheric): Aeroshell deploys from stowed configuration. HTPS and ESN perform Built-In Test (BIT). NADE initializes with current space weather data.
2. Entry Interface (EI ~120 km): ESN begins acquiring atmospheric data. State estimator initializes entry corridor. Baseline NPC active.
3. Peak Heating (~60-80 km): CBF-QP filter actively enforces $q_{max}$ constraint. Adaptive RL policy may be engaged if Safety Monitor approves. Aeroshell maintains fully deployed state.
4. Peak Deceleration (~40 km): CBF filter enforces $n_{max}$ constraint. Drag modulation may adjust aeroshell state to manage loads.
5. Terminal Guidance (~10 km): Aeroshell may retract partially to steepen trajectory for precision landing. Adaptive controller aims for $<100$ m target accuracy.
6. Parachute Deployment / Propulsive Landing: Vehicle transitions to terminal descent phase (outside scope of this entry-focused paper).

