8. Safety-Critical Control: CBF and Simplex Architecture

This chapter constitutes the formal mathematical core of the ADIC certification argument. We establish that the closed-loop system renders a predefined safe set $\mathcal{C}$ forward invariant, irrespective of the behavior of the uncertified adaptive controller $u_a$.

8.1 Preliminaries and System Definition

We recall the control-affine system model from Section 1.1:

\Sigma : \quad \dot{x} = f(x) + g(x) u + d(t) 

Where $x \in \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^6$, $u \in \mathcal{U} \subset \mathbb{R}^2$, and $d(t) \in \mathcal{D}$ is a bounded disturbance with $\|d(t)\| \le d_{max}$. The safe set $\mathcal{C}$ is defined as the zero-superlevel set of a continuously differentiable function $h : \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}$:

\mathcal{C} = \{ x \in \mathbb{R}^n : h(x) \ge 0 \} 

For entry, $h(x)$ is a composite barrier function (see Section 2.3) incorporating heat flux, load factor, and dynamic pressure constraints.

8.2 Zeroing Control Barrier Functions (ZCBF)

Definition 8.1 (ZCBF). A function $h : \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}$ is a Zeroing Control Barrier Function for $\mathcal{C}$ if there exists an extended class-$\mathcal{K}_\infty$ function $\alpha$ such that for all $x \in \mathcal{C}$:

\sup_{u \in \mathcal{U}} \left[ L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \alpha(h(x)) \right] \ge 0 

Definition 8.2 (Safe Control Set). The pointwise set of safe controls is:

\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x) = \{ u \in \mathcal{U} : L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \alpha(h(x)) \ge 0 \} 

Theorem 8.1 (Forward Invariance under ZCBF). If $h$ is a ZCBF for $\mathcal{C}$ and $u(t) \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x(t))$ for all $t \ge 0$, then $\mathcal{C}$ is forward invariant for the undisturbed system ($d \equiv 0$).

Proof. The time derivative of $h$ along trajectories satisfies:

\dot{h}(x) = L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u \ge -\alpha(h(x)) 

By the Comparison Lemma, $h(x(t)) \ge \nu(t)$ where $\dot{\nu} = -\alpha(\nu)$ with $\nu(0) = h(x(0))$. Since $\alpha \in \mathcal{K}_\infty$, $\nu(t) \ge 0$ for all $t \ge 0$ whenever $\nu(0) \ge 0$. Hence $x(t) \in \mathcal{C}$ for all $t \ge 0$. $\square$

8.3 Robust ZCBF for Bounded Disturbances

In practice, the system is subject to disturbances $d(t)$ and estimation error. We require a robust formulation.

Definition 8.3 (Robust ZCBF). A function $h$ is a Robust ZCBF for system $\Sigma$ if:

\sup_{u \in \mathcal{U}} \inf_{d \in \mathcal{D}} \left[ L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + L_d h(x) d + \alpha(h(x)) \right] \ge 0 

where $L_d h(x)$ is the Lie derivative along the disturbance direction.

Theorem 8.2 (Robust Forward Invariance). Assume $h$ is a Robust ZCBF and $\|L_d h(x)\| \le \gamma(x)$. If $\gamma(x) d_{max} \le \alpha(h(x))$ for all $x \in \partial\mathcal{C}$, then any controller $u(x) \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}^{robust}(x)$ renders $\mathcal{C}$ robustly forward invariant.

Proof. The worst-case disturbance satisfies $L_d h(x) d \ge -\|L_d h(x)\| d_{max} \ge -\gamma(x) d_{max}$. The robust CBF condition ensures:

\dot{h}(x) \ge -\alpha(h(x)) + \gamma(x) d_{max} - \gamma(x) d_{max} = -\alpha(h(x)) 

The remainder follows as in Theorem 8.1. $\square$

8.4 The Simplex Architecture: Formal Specification

The Simplex Architecture separates the control system into a certified baseline $u_b$ and an uncertified adaptive controller $u_a$, with a Safety Monitor $\mathcal{M}$ and a CBF-QP filter that enforces constraints.

Definition 8.4 (Simplex Control System). The system is defined by the tuple $(\Sigma, \mathcal{C}, u_b, u_a, \mathcal{M}, \pi)$ where:

· $u_b : \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{U}$ is the certified baseline controller, satisfying $u_b(x) \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$ for all $x \in \mathcal{C}$.
· $u_a : \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{U}$ is the adaptive controller (uncertified, e.g., RL policy).
· $\mathcal{M} : \mathcal{X} \times \mathcal{U} \to \{0,1\}$ is the Safety Monitor.
· $\pi$ is the control law:

 u = \begin{cases} 
\Pi_{\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)}(u_a) & \text{if } \mathcal{M}(x, u_a) = 1 \\
u_b(x) & \text{if } \mathcal{M}(x, u_a) = 0
\end{cases} 

where $\Pi_{\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)}$ denotes the Euclidean projection onto the safe control set.

Theorem 8.3 (Simplex Safety Preservation). Assume:

1. $u_b(x) \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$ for all $x \in \mathcal{C}$ (Baseline Safety).
2. $\mathcal{M}(x, u_a) = 1 \implies u_a \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$ (Monitor Soundness).
3. $\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x) \ne \emptyset$ for all $x \in \mathcal{C}$ (Control Authority).

Then the closed-loop system under $\pi$ renders $\mathcal{C}$ forward invariant, regardless of the behavior of $u_a$ .

Proof. We consider two cases:

Case 1: $\mathcal{M}(x, u_a) = 1$.
By condition 2, $u_a \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$. The projection $\Pi_{\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)}(u_a)$ returns a control $u^* \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$. By Theorem 8.1, applying $u^*$ ensures $\mathcal{C}$ remains invariant.

Case 2: $\mathcal{M}(x, u_a) = 0$.
The system applies $u_b(x)$. By condition 1, $u_b(x) \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$, so invariance is preserved.

Since $\mathcal{C}$ is invariant in both cases, and condition 3 guarantees a safe control always exists, $\mathcal{C}$ is forward invariant for all trajectories. $\square$

8.5 Safety Monitor Design

The Safety Monitor evaluates whether the proposed adaptive command $u_a$ satisfies the robust CBF constraint.

Definition 8.5 (CBF-Based Monitor). For a given margin $\epsilon \ge 0$:

\mathcal{M}_{CBF}(x, u_a) = \mathbb{I}\left[ L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u_a + \alpha(h(x)) \ge \epsilon \right] 

Theorem 8.4 (Soundness of CBF Monitor). $\mathcal{M}_{CBF}$ is sound for any $\epsilon \ge 0$.

Proof. If $\mathcal{M}_{CBF}(x, u_a) = 1$, then $L_f h + L_g h u_a + \alpha(h) \ge \epsilon \ge 0$, hence $u_a \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$. $\square$

Remark 8.1 (Margin $\epsilon$). A positive $\epsilon$ provides robustness to numerical errors and unmodeled dynamics. Larger $\epsilon$ increases safety margin but may reject more adaptive commands, reducing performance. The selection of $\epsilon$ is a critical design trade-off informed by Monte Carlo analysis.

8.6 CBF-Quadratic Program (CBF-QP) Filter

The projection $\Pi_{\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)}(u_a)$ is computed by solving a Quadratic Program (QP) at each control cycle.

Problem 8.1 (CBF-QP). Given a desired command $u_{des} \in \mathcal{U}$ (either $u_a$ or $u_b$), solve:

 \begin{aligned}
u^* = \arg\min_{u \in \mathbb{R}^m, \delta \in \mathbb{R}} \quad & \frac{1}{2} \|u - u_{des}\|^2 + \lambda \delta^2 \\
\text{subject to} \quad & L_f h_i(x) + L_g h_i(x) u + \alpha_i(h_i(x)) \ge -\delta, \quad i = 1,\dots,m \\
& u_{min} \le u \le u_{max}, \quad \delta \ge 0
\end{aligned} 

where $\delta$ is a slack variable (penalized heavily by $\lambda \gg 1$) that ensures feasibility even if the constraint cannot be strictly satisfied.

Theorem 8.5 (QP Properties). The CBF-QP has:

1. A unique solution due to strong convexity of the objective.
2. Lipschitz continuous solution $u^*(x)$ with respect to $x$ if the Linear Independence Constraint Qualification (LICQ) holds.

Proof. The Hessian is the identity matrix (positive definite). Linear constraints define a convex polyhedral feasible set. Strong convexity guarantees a unique global minimum. Solution continuity follows from standard parametric optimization theory under LICQ. $\square$

8.7 Handling State Estimation Error

The true state $x$ is not known; only an estimate $\hat{x}$ with bounded error $\|x - \hat{x}\| \le \varepsilon$ is available. To guarantee safety for the true system, we must tighten the CBF constraint.

Theorem 8.6 (Robust CBF under Estimation Error). Let $h$ be a ZCBF with Lipschitz constant $L_h$ for its gradient. If the CBF constraint is tightened by a margin $\Delta_{est} = L_h \cdot L_{dyn} \cdot \varepsilon$, where $L_{dyn}$ is a Lipschitz constant for the dynamics, then satisfaction of the tightened constraint on $\hat{x}$ implies satisfaction of the original constraint on $x$.

Proof. Using Lipschitz properties:

|L_f h(x) - L_f h(\hat{x})| \le L_h L_{dyn} \|x - \hat{x}\| \le \Delta_{est} 

Therefore, if $L_f h(\hat{x}) + L_g h(\hat{x}) u + \alpha(h(\hat{x})) \ge \Delta_{est}$, then:

L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \alpha(h(x)) \ge 0 

ensuring safety for the true state. $\square$

Implementation: The Safety Monitor and CBF-QP filter use the tightened constraint with margin $\Delta_{est}$ computed from the guaranteed estimator error bound $\varepsilon$.

8.8 Real-Time Computational Guarantee

For human-rating, the CBF-QP must execute deterministically within the control cycle.

Theorem 8.7 (Worst-Case Execution Time). For $m \le 5$ constraints and $n \le 2$ controls, using a fixed-iteration primal-dual interior point method with $k_{max} = 20$ iterations, the worst-case execution time on a 200 MHz LEON4 radiation-hardened processor is:

\text{WCET} \le 1.0 \text{ ms} 

Proof Sketch. Each iteration requires:

· Forming the KKT matrix: $\mathcal{O}(n^3) \approx 8$ operations.
· Cholesky factorization: $\mathcal{O}(n^3) \approx 8$ operations.
· Back-substitution and line search: $\mathcal{O}(n^2) \approx 4$ operations.

Total per iteration $\approx 20$ FLOPs (though memory access dominates). With 20 iterations and conservative assumptions about cache misses and FPU latency (10 cycles/FLOP), total cycles $\approx 200,000$. At 200 MHz, this yields 1.0 ms. A watchdog timer triggers fallback to $u_b$ if computation exceeds 1.5 ms. $\square$

