9. Entry Trajectory Modes

The ADIC guidance system can operate in multiple trajectory modes, each optimized for different mission phases or uncertainty conditions. The mode is selected either pre-planned or adaptively based on real-time state estimates.

9.1 Direct Entry Mode

Direct entry is the simplest and most robust trajectory. The vehicle enters the atmosphere and descends continuously without exo-atmospheric coasting.

Mathematical Characterization:
The trajectory satisfies $\gamma < 0$ for all $t \ge t_{EI}$, where $t_{EI}$ is entry interface. The altitude profile is monotonic decreasing. The peak heat flux and deceleration occur in a single pulse.

Advantages:

· Shortest total time from entry interface to landing ($\approx 8–12$ minutes for lunar return).
· Minimal guidance complexity; well-suited for emergency abort scenarios.
· Robust to large state estimation errors.

Disadvantages:

· Highest peak heat flux and deceleration loads.
· Limited downrange capability.

9.2 Skip Entry Mode

A skip entry utilizes aerodynamic lift to generate a positive flight path angle after initial atmospheric penetration, causing the vehicle to exit the sensible atmosphere temporarily before a second entry.

Mathematical Condition for Skip:
A skip trajectory is achieved when the vehicle attains $\gamma > 0$ at some altitude $h > h_{min}$, where $h_{min}$ is typically 60–70 km. The condition for lift to overcome gravity and drag is:

\frac{L \cos \sigma}{m v} > \frac{g \cos \gamma}{v} - \frac{v \cos \gamma}{r} 

Advantages:

· Reduced peak heat flux (distributed over two pulses).
· Extended downrange capability (up to 10,000 km for lunar return).
· Lower peak g-load.

Disadvantages:

· Longer total flight time ($\approx 20–30$ minutes).
· Increased total integrated heat load.
· Higher sensitivity to atmospheric modeling errors during the exit phase.
· Requires precise bank angle control to avoid unintended ballistic re-entry or escape.

9.3 Adaptive Trajectory Switching Logic

The ADIC introduces a novel adaptive switching capability that selects the optimal trajectory mode based on real-time uncertainty quantification.

Decision Criteria:
Let $P_{safe}(mode)$ be the estimated probability of satisfying all safety constraints under the current state uncertainty for a given mode. The mode selector maximizes a weighted combination of safety and performance:

\text{mode}^* = \arg\max_{m \in \{\text{direct, skip}\}} \left[ P_{safe}(m) + \lambda_{perf} \cdot J_{perf}(m) \right] 

Where $J_{perf}(m)$ is a performance metric (e.g., landing accuracy, crew comfort). The safety probability $P_{safe}(m)$ is computed online via Monte Carlo dropout or ensemble predictions from the NADE.

Switching Condition:
Switching is permitted only when:

1. The current trajectory state is within the "safe switching envelope" – a subset of $\mathcal{C}$ from which the new mode can be executed without violating constraints.
2. The CBF filter confirms that the initial control sequence for the new mode lies in $\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x)$.

Theorem 9.1 (Safe Mode Switching). If the system switches from mode A to mode B at state $x_{switch}$, and there exists a control policy $u_B(t)$ for mode B such that $x(t) \in \mathcal{C}$ for all $t \ge t_{switch}$, and the CBF-QP filter is active, then the closed-loop system remains safe post-switch.

Proof. The CBF-QP filter enforces $u(t) \in \mathcal{U}_{safe}(x(t))$ at all times, regardless of the commanded mode. Therefore, even if the new mode's nominal control would violate constraints, the filter projects it to safety. The existence of a safe control policy for mode B guarantees $\mathcal{U}_{safe}(x_{switch}) \ne \emptyset$, so the filter can find a feasible control. $\square$

9.4 Mode Transition Logic

