12.5 Limitations of the Current Study

This paper has focused on the entry phase of a lunar return mission. The following areas are acknowledged as outside the scope and represent opportunities for future work:

1. Transonic and Subsonic Aerodynamics: The deployable aeroshell's stability and control characteristics in the transonic regime ($M \approx 0.8–1.2$) require additional CFD and wind tunnel validation.
2. Parachute Deployment Interface: The interaction between the deployed aeroshell wake and drogue parachute inflation is not modeled. This is a critical multi-body dynamics problem.
3. Propulsive Landing Integration: The paper assumes a traditional parachute/airbag or propulsive terminal descent. Integration with a propulsive lander (e.g., Starship or Blue Moon) would alter the entry target accuracy requirements.
4. Crew Physiological Response: While g-load constraints are enforced, a detailed biomechanical model of crew tolerance to sustained acceleration and vibration is not included.

12.6 Conclusion on Risks

The ADIC architecture, through its Simplex-CBF safety core and deployable aeroshell, provides a defensible, certifiable path to integrating advanced adaptive control into human-rated spacecraft. The identified risks are manageable within standard aerospace engineering practices, and the formal safety proofs provide a level of assurance that meets or exceeds current human-rating requirements. The system does not eliminate uncertainty—no system can—but it provides a mathematically guaranteed bounded response to that uncertainty.

13. Future Work

The ADIC architecture presented in this paper establishes a theoretical and analytical foundation for a certifiably safe, adaptive entry vehicle. However, translating this concept into a flight-qualified human-rated system requires a structured progression through simulation, ground testing, and incremental flight demonstrations. This chapter outlines a prioritized roadmap for future research and development.

13.1 High-Fidelity Simulation and Validation

The analytical proofs and Monte Carlo results presented herein rely on reduced-order dynamical models (6-DOF point mass) and parameterized atmospheric dispersions. The immediate next step is validation in a high-fidelity simulation environment.

13.1.1 Multi-Body Dynamics with Flexible Structures
The deployable aeroshell is not a rigid body. Fluid-structure interaction (FSI) between the hypersonic flow and the flexible TPS fabric, as well as modal coupling between the inflatable toroid and the mechanical ribs, must be characterized. Future work will couple a Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) solver (e.g., NASA DPLR or US3D) with a nonlinear Finite Element Model (FEM) of the deployed structure to:

· Quantify aeroelastic flutter boundaries.
· Validate the aerodynamic coefficient database $C_L(\alpha, M, \delta)$ and $C_D(\alpha, M, \delta)$.
· Refine the robust CBF margin $\Delta_{est}$ to account for unmodeled flexible dynamics.

13.1.2 Transonic and Supersonic Transition
The current analysis focuses on the hypersonic entry phase. The transition through transonic Mach numbers ($M \approx 1.2 \to 0.8$) introduces separated flow, dynamic instability, and potential for parachute mortar interference. A dedicated study using Detached Eddy Simulation (DES) will characterize the wake structure behind the deployed aeroshell and define the safe separation envelope for drogue parachute deployment.

13.1.3 End-to-End Entry, Descent, and Landing (EDL) Simulation
The current work terminates at terminal guidance. Future work will integrate the ADIC entry phase with models of parachute inflation, heatshield jettison (if applicable), and propulsive terminal descent. This end-to-end simulation will validate the 100 m landing accuracy target in the context of the complete EDL sequence.

13.2 Hardware-in-the-Loop (HIL) Testing

Formal verification of the CBF-QP solver and Simplex logic must be complemented by real-time Hardware-in-the-Loop testing on flight-like avionics.

13.2.1 Processor-in-the-Loop (PIL)
The CBF-QP solver (Section 8.8) will be cross-compiled for a LEON4 development board and subjected to worst-case input injection to empirically validate the 1.0 ms WCET bound. A fault injection campaign will simulate single-event upsets (SEU) to verify watchdog fallback behavior.

13.2.2 Sensor Emulation
The ESN data stream will be emulated using a real-time thermal response model of the HTPS. This will validate the Set-Valued Observer's convergence and bounded-error properties under realistic sensor noise and simulated failures (e.g., loss of stagnation pressure transducer).

13.2.3 Flight Software Integration
The complete GN&C stack (NPC, NADE inference, RL policy, CBF-QP, Simplex switch) will be integrated into a Core Flight System (cFS) architecture and tested for timing determinism and inter-process communication latency.

13.3 TPS Material Coupon Testing

The performance of the Hybrid TPS, particularly the interface between the ablative layer and the HEEET hot structure, requires empirical validation beyond analytical models.

13.3.1 Arc-Jet Testing Campaign
Instrumented HTPS coupons (with embedded thermocouples and heat flux gauges) will be exposed to simulated lunar return heat flux profiles in an arc-jet facility (e.g., NASA Ames Interaction Heating Facility). Objectives include:

· Validation of variable-thickness recession models.
· Measurement of char layer adhesion and spallation resistance.
· Characterization of bondline temperature history for structural margin verification.

13.3.2 3D-Woven Sensor Integration
Coupons of HEEET-class material with embedded Fiber Bragg Grating (FBG) fibers will be subjected to combined thermal and mechanical loading to validate strain measurement accuracy and fiber survivability through the weaving and curing process.

13.4 Real-Time Control Benchmarking

The adaptive RL policy (Section 7.4) was trained offline. Future work will explore online adaptation strategies that update the policy or the NADE model in real time using the ESN data stream.

13.4.1 Meta-Learning for Rapid Atmosphere Adaptation
Instead of a fixed NADE, a meta-learned model that adapts its weights after observing a few seconds of ESN pressure data could provide faster convergence to the true density profile. This must be balanced against the certification constraint that the safety core remain independent of any online learning process.

13.4.2 Benchmarking Against Optimal Control
The RL policy's performance will be benchmarked against a numerically solved optimal control problem (e.g., using GPOPS-II or DIDO) for a set of reference trajectories to quantify the optimality gap. This will establish whether further performance gains are achievable within the safe envelope.

13.5 Formal Verification Integration

The Simplex safety proof (Theorem 8.3) is a paper proof. For human-rating certification, this proof must be mechanized in a theorem prover.

13.5.1 Coq/Isabelle Formalization
The ZCBF forward invariance theorem and the Simplex switching logic will be formalized in the Coq proof assistant. This will provide an independently verifiable artifact that the safety properties hold for all possible inputs within the specified bounds.

13.5.2 SMT-Based QP Solver Verification
The C++ implementation of the fixed-iteration interior point solver will be verified using Satisfiability Modulo Theories (SMT) solvers (e.g., CBMC) to prove the absence of runtime errors (division by zero, array out-of-bounds) and to verify that the output $u^*$ satisfies the linear CBF constraints within numerical tolerance.

13.6 Subscale Flight Demonstration

The ultimate validation of the ADIC architecture is a subscale orbital or suborbital flight test.

13.6.1 Sounding Rocket Test (TRL 6–7)
A subscale version of the deployable aeroshell (e.g., 1.5 m diameter) could be lofted on a sounding rocket to an apogee of 200–300 km, providing a re-entry velocity of 2–3 km/s. This would validate deployment dynamics, TPS performance, and the ESN data acquisition in a relevant environment.

13.6.2 Orbital Re-Entry Experiment
A hosted payload on a commercial resupply vehicle (e.g., Cygnus or Dragon trunk) could deploy a small-scale ADIC test article for a destructive re-entry, transmitting ESN data via Iridium or TDRSS until blackout. This would provide the first flight validation of the Simplex-CBF safety filter in a closed-loop hypersonic environment.

